message: Fixed PlayerController rotation with Head Controller rotation in the y axis
Fixed input names for Bluetooth controller
Fixed input names for bluetooth controller

4 buttons of remote control :video_game:  completely functional :+1:  #12

Now we can use the four buttons (X,Y,A,B) for moving the main character
at the Dungeon Game

Fixing visibility Issue :camera: :eyes:

Whe you walk through the corridor you can see sometimes the blue sky
through the wall.. to fix it I just change the background color of the
skybox to black.
Making bigger the world and growing up the player

Added monster and event emitter for running :japanese_goblin:

Now when the player reach a determine area the monster starts to run
through you
Added sound to monster.. take your diapers

Agrouping foldersand use sample menu

Reorganize folder of sound and remove replicate folder script,
scripts.... And proposed to use (modified) demo menu from GoogleVR
sample. Adding spanish dic for voice recognition

message: added missing brickwall compression, unified materials folder.

capacity calculation, create capacitor plate resize object to allow the player to resize the plate size by him own.

added chain with custom inspector to create custom chains/cables with different characteristics
Merge branch 'viveVR5.5' of https://github.com/JoeyPrink/physicsLab into viveVR5.5

fixed reset simulation bug, so that no current remains after reset
added move controller for all moveable objects
Screen graph gets the value from specified method with special message arguments

Merge branch 'viveVR5.5' of https://github.com/JoeyPrink/Maroon into viveVR5.5

# Conflicts:
#	ProjectSettings/ProjectVersion.txt
Removed empty folder. Fixed Project Version File.
Moved ExampleScenes in 'External Projects' for a better overview.
Rearranged MyAssets Folder. Removed unnecassary test scenes.

fixed lightning bolt camera moving bug
fixed grounder movement
fixed trigger haptic pulse for magnetic force

added new experiment scene
* water basin
* wave generator
* custom water surface shader
updated configuration to fix some validations tests
added example tests from starter kit
changed displayName and updated settings to latest trunk

First template commit (#1)

* First template commit. OpenVR input not working.

* fixed and moved Tests folder

* added missing file from previous change

* updated settings for 2019.2

* changed from mac to Windows64 like HDRP

* rebuilt vfx assets

* added visualeffectgraph to package dependencies

chore(README): format title

Remove the underscores from the title for better readability.

chore(gitignore): add relevant system files

The OSX .DS_Store and the vim *.swp files have been added to the
ignore file in case someone is developing on a mac or using vim for coding.

chore(setup): add base unity project

The Toolkit will be built into Unity to hold the scripts, prefabs and
example files.

feat(Device): add basic headset and controller tracking

This utilises the SteamVR plugin from the Unity Asset Store and
provides a basic `CameraRig` prefab that enables the headset tracking
in the game world along with controller tracking and creates the
controller models.

The actual prefab used is not the one from the SteamVR prefabs folder
as it seems to be missing the relevant controller elements but there
is a version of the prefab in the `SteamVR_TestThrow` scene that
contains all of the relevant elements so this is the one that has been
copied to the project's `Prefabs` directory.

A basic example scene has been added that demonstrates the `CameraRig`
headset and controller tracking.

message:
feat(Controller): add button event listener script

A new Controller Events script has been added that listens for the
interactions with the VR controller and emits an event when a button
is pressed or released (also touched in the case of the touchpad).
It also holds the current state of each action in a public boolean
so it's possible to determine if a button is being continually held
down.

A new example scene has been added which demonstrates the Controller
events along with an example script which just logs the captured events
to the console.

feat(Pointer): add simple pointer for highlighting game items

A new `SimplePointer` script has been added that is attached to a
VR Controller in the `CameraRig` prefab and provides a basic laser
beam to be emitted from the end of the controller.

When the beam collides with another object in the game world, the
pointer emits an event along with a payload of the item it has
collided with and the distance the controller is from the object.

A new example scene has been added which demonstrates the Pointer as
well as demonstrates the events along with an example script which just
logs the pointer events to the console.

The `Unlit/Color` shader has been added to the project settings to
ensure it is included at build time otherwise the laser beam
won't be able to be created.

docs(README): add initial documentation of project and contents

The initial documentation provides a basic overview and understanding
of the contents of the repository.

feat(Pointer): add new event for giving pointer end position

A new `PointerDestinationSet` event is now emitted when the pointer
beam is deactivated and the event payload now contains the world
position of the pointer tip which can be used to determine the position
in the world where the pointer was hitting.

This can be useful for determining where to teleport a player to by
listening to this new event and using the tip position variable to
move the player position to.

The accompanying example script has been updated to show this event.

feat(Pointer): separate pointer events into abstract class

The new `SteamVR_WorldPointer` abstract class now provides the events
and the payload for any pointer implementation such as the
`SteamVR_SimplePointer` as this will enable reusability across any
number of pointer scripts.

feat(Teleport): add basic teleport script for moving in game world

The Basic Teleport script allows the player to update their x/z
position in the game world by listening to a World Pointer event that
is emitted by another script (e.g. Controller with the SimplePointer
script attached).

Upon receiving the event, the script fades the screen, updates the
`[CameraRig]` position and unfades the screen.

A new example scene has been added which demonstrates the teleporting
functionality.

feat(Interaction): add ability to interact and grab objects

The two scripts that have been added work together by the
`SteamVR_ObjectGrab` script being assigned to a Controller and the
`SteamVR_InteractableObject` script being assigned to any object that
is to be picked up by the controller.

A new example scene has been added which demonstrates the object
interaction and grabbing.

feat(ObjectGrab): improve fidelity of object throw velocity

Utilising the `TrackedController` to determine it's origin velocity
provides a more fluid and realistic throwing velocity.

chore(structure): move project files into a more appropriate location

The previous file structure put everything into the `Resources`
directory but this made it harder to separate the actual toolkit and
so it is now all self contained in it's own directory making it easier
to simply drag and drop the toolkit into a new project.

message:
chore(Interaction): rename ObjectGrab to something more generic

The previous `ObjectGrab` script is going to be doing more than
just grabbing objects. It will be the place for any controller/object
interaction so a more appropriate name has been given to it.

feat(Controller): add custom button alias events

The Controller Events script now has three common action aliases:

  * Pointer Toggle
  * Interact Toggle
  * Menu Toggle

These aliases can be set to whichever button is desired to trigger them
and the other scripts now listen for the alias event rather than the
button event meaning their actions can be configured to a specific
button.

So now the Simple Pointer listens for the Pointer Toggle event and
therefore doesn't need to be tied to pressing the grip button.

And the Controller Interact script listens for the Interact Toggle
event rather than the Trigger so the interaction button can be
customised.

feat(Interaction): emit events when controller interacts with objects

The `SteamVR_ControllerInteract` script now emits events when the
controller touches/untouches or grabs/ungrabs an interactable object.

It is also possible for a global touch colour to be specified on the
Controller Interact script rather than applying the colour to all
interactable objects. However, the interactable objects can still have
a touch highlight colour which will override any global touch colour.

The example scene has been updated with a console output for the events
and also shows off the global touch hightlight colour.

feat(ControllerInteract): add ability to hide controller model

There are two new flags on the Controller Interact script:

  * Hide Controller On Touch
  * Hide Controller On Grab

If they are ticked then the controller model will disappear either
when touching an interactable object or grabbing it (depending on
the flag that is checked).

If Hide on Touch is checked then it will naturally be hidden on
grab without needing to tick the checkbox.

feat(Interaction): add ability to use an interactable object

The Interactable Objects can now also be used as well as grabbed.
A used object just triggers an action to take place on the object
rather than pick the object up and snap it to the controller.

An example scene has been added that demonstrates a usable door by
opening and closing the door when the controller interacts with it.

fix(Teleport): ensure the headset offset is taken into consideration

Previously, when teleporting, the `[CameraRig]` play area centre would
always be where the new teleport location was and it would be jarring
as the headset location within the play area wasn't accounted for.

This fix ensures the headset location within the play area is
compensated so the headset location ends up at the teleported location
and not the actual play area.

feat(Teleport): add teleportation to different object heights

A new Height Adjust Teleporter has been created that is extended from
the Basic Teleporter (which has now been updated to allow other
teleporters to inherit the Basic Teleport).

The Height Adjust Teleporter will check to see if the beam tip is on
top of the target object and if it is then the new teleport Y location
will be on top of that object, which enables climbing up objects in
the game world.

There is an additional flag of `playAreaFalling` that determines if
the player should fall down to the nearest floor if they step into
a part of the play area that is not on the object they are standing on.

If this flag is turned off then they will not fall down and can hover
in the air as their play area is fixed to the Y of the object they
currently standing on.

A new example scene has been added to show the new height adjust
teleporter working.

fix(Teleport): ensure headset eye object is found

For some reason in versions of Unity (maybe 5.4 beta) the Camera
model underneath the CameraRig prefab gets put at the top level
at run time so the Cemera is no longer a child of the CameraRig.

This causes an issue where the `eyeCamera` cannot be set because
no children exist that have the `SteamVR_GameView` script on them.

As there will only ever be one Game View (i.e. headset) in the
game world then it is an appropriate fix to just find that object
in the entire game world rather than just looking in the children of
the CameraRig prefab.

chore(Interaction): separate the object interaction code

Previously all of the object interactions like touch, grab and use all
existed in the same script (`SteamVR_ControllerInteract`) which meant
that one script was doing a lot and made it very difficult to customise
functionality without growing the script.

Now these three interactions have been separated into their own scripts
although the grab and use scripts require the touch script to also be
applied to the Controller as they use the `touched` object state to
know which object to interact with.

A new Controller Event has also been added to separate grabbing from
using. So by default both interactions use the Controller `Trigger`
but it's now possible to set a different button to grab and to use.

chore(README): apply consistent formatting

The text had inconsistent structure like the way lists were laid out or how scripts were described.

chore(README): remove line breaks for lists

The bullet lists look odd with the additional line breaks in them.

feat(Interaction): example scene to show grabbed object being used

The new example scene `008_Controller_UsingAGrabbedObject` has a couple
of objects on a table that can be picked up with the `Grip` button and
whilst they are picked up can be used with the `Trigger` button.

chore(Interaction): rename the using a door example

To be consistent with other examples, it's now just prefixed with
`Controller` as the `ControllerInteract` script no longer exists so
this prefix no longer is relevant.

feat(Pointer): add bezier curve pointer

The Bezier Pointer always shows a cursor on the top of any object and
draws a bezier curve to the ground cursor so it is easier to see where
the teleport location will end up.

A helper file has been added that takes care of calculating the bezier
curve and plotting a collection of spheres through it to simulate the
pointer beam over a curve. This bezier curve code is heavily inspired
by the code and tutorial at:
`http://catlikecoding.com/unity/tutorials/curves-and-splines/`

It is possible to set a valid beam colour and an invalid beam colour
which will determine if the beam has found a valid floor to land on.

A new example has been added to show the new Bezier Pointer working
with teleportation.

Merge pull request #15 from thestonefox/feat/bezierpointer

feat(Pointer): add bezier curve pointer

chore(Pointer): add default target colours for pointer

As the shader is a transparent shader, the default colour when not
set is `Color.clear` which is also transparent which causes
confusion for users when using the script as the valid and invalid
target colours both have an alpha of zero.

This means that it's easy to set the colour of the target but forget
about setting the alpha so it seems as if the beams are broken but
in fact they are just completely transparent.

A simple solution is to just default the target colours with a
translucent colour so it's less confusing to new users.

feat(Interaction): add ability to trigger actions on touch events

Previously, the grab and use event could trigger actions in the
Interactable Object script (or scripts that extend it) but it was not
possible to override a method to deal with touching or stop touching.

The Interactable Object now supports overridable methods for
`StartTouching` and `StopTouching` and also sets a new flag of
`isTouching` on the object.

The Interact Touch class now also calls the Interactable Object touch
methods when the controller touches or stops touching the object.

feat(Teleport): add ability to traverse terrain objects

The Basic Teleport now determines the Y position of the play area
based on the terrain height underneath the player. This means that
if the teleport location is on a terrain object then the Y position
of the play area is adjusted to the correct height of the terrain
mesh.

This means it is now possible to traverse terrains using either the
Basic or Height Adjust Teleporters.

A new example scene has been added to show this terrain traversal.

fix(Teleport): ensure headset compensation works correctly

Previously, the headset compensation was not working and would
always set the teleport location to the centre of the play area.

This has now been fixed and a new `Headset Position Compensation`
option on the script has been added to toggle it.

Also, the basic teleporter can no longer traverse terrains as it
caused too many issues with an incorrect Y value on normal objects.

feat(Headset): add headset collision fading

This script is attached to the `Camera (head)` object within the
`[CameraRig]` prefab and adds a box collider and rigidbody to the
headset object. When the headset collides with another collidable
object, the trigger fades the headset view to a given colour.

This is to prevent the player from putting their head into objects
and seeing unwanted object clipping artifacts.

An example scene has been added to demonstrate the new script.

Merge pull request #18 from thestonefox/feat/headsetcollision

feat(Headset): add headset collision fading

feat(Controller): add button type axis change events

The controller contains two button type axis, the touchpad which is an
x/y axis determining the location on the touchpad that is being touched
and the trigger which is an x axis determining how hard the trigger is
being depressed.

A new `buttonPressed` variable is emitted in the event payload that
for all other buttons because they are digital emits either 1f on press
or 0f on release to represent their pressure. The trigger will have a
varying pressure based on the trigger axis value.

The `SteamVR_ControllerEvents_ListenerExample.cs` script has been
updated to log out these extra axis events.

feat(Pointer): add play area cursor option to all pointers

The World Pointer abstract class now generates a play area cursor
that can be projected on to the end of any cursor that extends it.

The play area cursor can also handle collisions on the cursor end and
determine if the play area will be obstructed by other objects within
the cursor location. This can then be used to prevent teleporting
which will prevent players being in locations that they can clip into
objects.

The Simple Pointer and Bezier Pointer have been refactored so their
code that is the same between the two classes now sits in the World
Pointer class (as it's generic to all pointers). This provides the
two child pointers with more default parameters that are generic to
all child pointers as well.

The `Interfaces` directory has been renamed to `Abstractions` as the
World Pointer class isn't actually an interface so made no sense
calling the containing directory `Interfaces`.

A custom shader has been written to allow for Unlit Transparent colours
which work well with the pointers.

An example has been added that shows how the play area with collision
can be used to prevent players from teleporting to locations that would
mean they have the potential to walk into objects.

Merge pull request #22 from thestonefox/feat/playarea_pointer_cursor

feat(Pointer): add play area cursor option to all pointers

chore(README): add youtube example tour links

There are a number of Example tours on YouTube which explain the example scenes.

feat(Interaction): add ability to not need to hold buttons to interact

Previously, the grab button was required to be held down to continue
holding an object and the use button was also required to be held down
to ensure an object's Using state was active.

Now the Interactable Object script has two new parameters:

  * `holdButtonToGrab`
  * `holdButtonToUse`

If these parameters are checked then the previous action of needing to
hold the button down to perform the action is still used.

However, if they are unchecked then the user will have to press the
button once to initiate the action (e.g. press to grab) then they no
longer have to continually hold the button down to keep doing the
action (e.g. keep grabbing). When they want to stop doing the action
they press the button again (e.g. to stop grabbing).

This adds the benefit that multiple items can be set into their Using
state at any one time.

A new example scene shows this in action. The example scene has a red
barrel gun which demonstrates that setting the `holdButtonToUse`
parameter to unchecked doesn't always produce a good effect, in this
case the gun only fires on every other trigger press.

fix(Interaction): prevent crash on interaction button press

When no object is being touched and an interaction button is pressed
a crash would occur due to no `obj` existing and therefore the
`GetComponent` method not being able to be called on a null object.

The fix is to ensure `obj` is valid before continuing.

feat(Interaction): add ability to snap object rotation on grab

The Interactable Object script now has an additional parameter of:

  * `snapToRotation`

This parameter is a `Vector3` that determines the rotation of the
object when it is grabbed. To not set a rotation, the parameter
should be left as `0,0,0` (Vector3.zero).

When a snap rotated object is grabbed, the collisions on the object
are paused for a fraction of a second to prevent colliding with objects
that the grabbed object is on or near.

A new example scene has been created to demonstrate this functionality.

Merge pull request #24 from thestonefox/feat/snap-objects-on-grab

feat(Interaction): add ability to snap object rotation on grab

fix(Interaction): ensure lightsaber active state is set

The `beamActive` variable on the lightsaber script was never set.

feat(Interaction): add example to show touchpad axis control

A new example has been added that contains an R/C car that is
controlled by moving a finger across the touchpad. Moving up and down
on the touchpad causese the car to drive forward and backward, moving
left and right causes the car to turn in that direction.

The trigger axis is also used to determine how high the car will jump
when the trigger is pressed.

feat(Interaction): add varying grab snap mechanics

Previously, only two snap mechanics were included, this has now been
formalised and an additional mechanic has been added. A new script
parameter has been added to the Interactable Object, the
`Grab Snap Type` determines which grab mechanic an interactable object
will use and can be one of three types:

  * `Simple_Snap`
  * `Rotation_Snap`
  * `Precision_Snap`

The `Simple_Snap` is the original grab snap mechanic where an object
is just centered to the controller position. The `Rotation_Snap` is
the rotational snap mechanism driven by the `Snap To Rotation`
parameter. The new mechanic is the `Precision_Snap` which does not
change the object's rotation or position so it simulates a hand
picking up an object with precision.

The example scene `Examples/014_Controller_SnappingObjectsOnGrab` has
been updated to demonstrate these new snap mechanics.

feat(Controller): add method to trigger controller vibration

A new method has been added to the `ControllerEvents` called
`TriggerHapticPulse(int duration, ushort strength)` that initiates
the haptic vibration in the controller for the given length of time
and vibrates at the given strength.

chore(README): add youtube example tour links

Added more youtube tour links for scenes 010 to 015.

chore(README): add faq/troubleshooting section

To try and address some common issues people may have, a new section
to the readme has been added that will cover these topics. Additional
videos will be added to Youtube where appropriate to aid in the solution.

chore(structure): remove inclusion of steamvr plugin

The SteamVR plugin is no longer included in this repository and needs
to be downloaded separately from the Unity Asset Store. This means that
upgrading the plugin will be independent of this toolkit keeping a
cleaner separation of concerns.

To ensure the separation can take place, a new script called
`SteamVR_ControllerActions` has been added that handles the hiding
of the controller models as this was originally added to the code
within the SteamVR plugin script `SteamVR_TrackerController`.

All of the example scenes that require to hide the controller now have
this new script added to the controllers so they function correctly.
The `SteamVR_InteractTouch` script will throw an error if it is
attached to a controller object that does not have the new
`SteamVR_ControllerActions` script attached to it.

Initial Check-in of the new vNext folder structure

A little empty here but us chickens (and default readme files)

Reset asset files for a clean break.
Added some missing readme's :S
Odd, git ignored the new .asset files.  Updating (again)
Updated Unity version numbers in ProjectSettings.asset file
Created a new MixedRealityToolkit-Examples folder and moved the old SDK examples in to it.  As well as creating a new "Internal" examples folder.

Merge pull request #1773 from DDReaper/MRTK-Version-Next_FolderStructure

Initial Check-in of the new vNext folder structure

Starter for 10, some of the core internal definitions and constructs.
This PR also demonstrates documentation expectations and detail required on all submitted code.
Renamed InputType to ControllerInputType base don feedback
Added namespaces, license headers and summary tags

Merge pull request #9 from SimonDarksideJ/MRTK-Version-Next_codingupdate

Coding standards tweaks

Update CodingGuidelines.md

some formatting changes and added a section for xml summary tags for documentation generation.

Update CodingGuidelines.md

fixed spelling error, added property/field co-location

Merge pull request #1846 from StephenHodgson/MRTK-Version-Next

MRTK vNEXT coding guidelines

Missed change for updating the Inputtype to ControllerInputType
Updated Unity version to latest beta
Upstream Merge, InputType rename fix and project updated to 2018.1 (version file left unchanged until it's released.)

Initial Check-in for Mixed Reality Manager
Updated project version to 2018.1.0b13

Updated Namespaces to new format
Added Initial Check-in of MixedRealityManager and accompanying dependencies.

*Note Not yet documented to standards.

Updated with review comments:

* Fixed spacings (#doh cut and paste)
* Fixed Definitions namespace (#doh, darn keyboard)
Added Flags and BitFields to ButtonAction and InputActions scripts

Updated scripts as per new standards
Updating ButtonAction based on feedback.
Removed fixed values for enums to auto-initialisation
Last reordering of Enum fields for clarity
Reordered SDKType to allow for more SDK's
